## `About me`

Hi y'all! I'm from Texas and will be a senior at the University of North
Texas this fall. I'm obtaining a BS in ecology with a minor in
sustainability and chemistry. This summer I participated in the USC
Wrigley Institute REU working with Dr. Melissa Guzman and PhD student
Jenny Cheung in the Ecological Data Science Lab.

I haven't always been the biggest nature/science person, until one high
school teacher opened me up to the world of environmental science and I
found myself very drawn to it. I then knew what to do for college but
never would have pictured myself completing a research project in a
program like this one, let alone knew what doing scientific research
was. Now that I'm here, I feel very grateful to get to pursue a degree
aligned with my passion, along with being chosen to work with the
amazing folks here at USC.

## `My Summer project`

I've completed a research project using open access data from the
National Ecological Observatory Network (NEON) to find patterns and
dissimilarities between soil communities across the United States. For
the purposes of my project, I have designated a "soil community" to be a
simple food web between ground beetles, small mammals and birds. I'm
also incorporating environmental parameters into my analysis by using
precipitation and air temperature NEON data to analyze distribution
patterns. Using these data sets allows me to find out what environmental
conditions or community interactions are driving the composition of soil
communities at a continental scale. My summer has been filled with
coding in "R" or "RStudio," which is a coding program used by ecologists
to visualize/analyze data.

## `Learning and moving forward`

The best and worst thing I have discovered this summer is that there are
limitless possibilities in terms of academic and career choices. As
someone who didn't know exactly which direction to go in, this aspect
used to appear as more of a looming consequence. The best part however,
is that as the program went on and I learned more about myself in a
scientific setting, the idea of endless possibilities is actually great!
There are so many valuable resources and outlets when it comes to
pursuing a career in ecology, not to mention the amazing mentors and
people you will meet along the way.

I've learned that I'm interested in pursuing higher education which I
was hesitant of before. Seeing all of the highly motivated researchers
at USC is a very eye opening experience, and it made the prospect of
grad school much more approachable. The main piece of wisdom I believe
to have gained while here is that knowledge truly is power, not just in
scientific advancement. Knowing your weak spots, strengths and
boundaries is so vital in order to persist in a field that is hard to
navigate. This program has revealed such aspects of myself and I look
forward to expanding my mindset in this way as I navigate my career.
